Rogers explicitly connects Dewey's theory of inquiry to his religious, moral, and political philosophy. He argues that, contrary to common belief, Dewey sought a place for religious commitment within a democratic society sensitive to modern pluralism. Against those who regard Dewey as indifferent to moral conflict, Rogers points to Dewey's appreciation for the incommensurability of our ethical commitments. His deep respect for modern pluralism, argues Rogers, led Dewey to articulate a negotiation between experts and the public so that power did not lapse into domination. Exhibiting an abiding faith in the reflective and contestable character of inquiry, Dewey strongly engaged with the complexity of our religious, moral, and political lives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066254208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044247208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014z978311045952440uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/roge14486423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231516167.jpg  a978-3-11-044247-2  CUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013  a978-3-11-045952-4  CUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014c2000d2014  a978-3-11-066254-2  CUP eBook Package 2000-2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG